* download cygwin, ensure rsync, tmux, git, parallel (not a package, figure this out) are selected
* merge world altering plugins to <file.esp || pcvgen.esp>
* pcvgen -o <file.esp || pcvgen.esp>
* start ck, load pcvgen.esp and all masters
* generate pc for world
* generate pc for interiors
* save and exit
* open up <file.esp || pcvgen.esp> in xEdit, run pcv script to create separate precombine merge plugins, save on exit.
* pcvgen: hardlink clone of base directory to per-<master> merge instance, enable VC for each
* pcvgen: merge (checkinplugin) each generated <master>_precombines_merge.esp into <master>
  * alternatively do this serially first so that all masters have been updated before previs gen
* pcvgen: CreationKit.exe -generateprevisdata:<master> clean all
* pcvgen: mv <instance>/PreVis.esp to <master>_previs_merge.esp
* either (one of):
  * open everything in xedit and post-merge/finalize into pcvgen.esp
  * -checkinplugin of each previs_merge.esp and extract all cells afterwards via xedit.

---

revised after testing:

* ensure any tree mods have appropriate occlusion settings, generate scols, and drop loose files in place before any gen
* ckgen manual world ints, load all desired plugins, ck1: precombine for world, ck2: precombine for ints
* save as pcv.esp and exit
* open up pcv.esp in xedit and run pcv script in precombine mode, save generated plugins
* merge all plugins with pcpvmerge or ckgen merge + some options not written yet
* ckgen previs clean main <all desired masters/plugins>
* rsync ckgen Data/ dirs in master/plugin order into Data/
* open up all previs_merge.esp plugins in master/plugin order (xedit + -P <file>) and run pcv script in previs mode.
* archive Data/Meshes/PreCombined and Data/Vis into pcv-final.ba2
* alter DLCList.txt and Plugins.txt

---

* Figure out what to do with each master's Vis files that aren't part of the Commonwealth. Surely there will be worldspace mods outside of the Commonwealth, so it shouldn't just be focused only on that, but how to handle generated files that aren't actually different than the vanilla files? Precombines are hashed (somehow) so they *should* be safe to detect for uniqueness. UVDs are per cell and not hashed, however they affect a 3x3 grid of cells and if any of the cells sharing the same RVIS key are altered from vanilla then the newly generated UVD file must be used.

